{{Chinese|float=left|showflag=p|t=去中國化|s=去中国化|l=De-Chinese-ization|p=qù zhōng guó huà|bpmf=ㄑㄩˋㄓㄨㄙ ㄍㄨㄛˊㄏㄨㄚˋ|y=heui jūng gwok fa|hangul=탈중국화|hanja=脫中國化|lk=De-Chinese-ization|rr=taljung-gughwa}}

'''De-Sinicization''' (''de''  + ''[[Sinicization]]'') is the elimination of Chinese influence.

==Historical==
Han dynasty General [[Li Ling]] defected to the [[Xiongnu]] and married a daughter of the Xiongnu Chanyu and acculturated to Xiongnu customs.

People of mixed ancestry or desinicized [[Han Chinese]] who adopted steppe people's culture and way of life existed in the sixth and seventh centuries A.D., and some even served in the [[Sui dynasty|Sui]] and [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] Dynasties' military.<ref>{{cite book |title=A history of Chinese civilization |author=Jacques Gernet |year=1996 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location= |isbn=978-0-521-49781-7 |page=248 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=jqb7L-pKCV8C&dq=0521497817 |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref>

[[Xianbei]] last names were adopted by Han Chinese as was Xianbei culture, militarism and clothing.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-last=Mullaney |editor1-first=Thomas |editor2-last=Leibold |editor2-first=James |editor3-last=Gros |editor3-first=Stephane |editor4-last=Bussche |editor4-first=Eric Vanden |title=Critical Han Studies: The History, Representation, and Identity of China's Majority |date=2012 |publisher=University of California Press |isbn=9780984590988 |url=http://scholar.harvard.edu/files/elliott/files/critical_han_studies_ch8_elliott.pdf?m=1360758785 |language=English}}|page= 181</ref> The Xianbei language was learned by several Han in the northern dynasties.<ref name="Skaff2012">{{cite book |author=Jonathan Karam Skaff |title=Sui-Tang China and Its Turko-Mongol Neighbors: Culture, Power, and Connections, 580-800 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5OpoAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA127#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=6 July 2012 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-987590-0 |pages=127–}}</ref> Xianbei surnames were assigned to Han troops and officers in the Northern Zhou.<ref name="Pan1997">{{cite book |author=Yihong Pan |title=Son of Heaven and Heavenly Qaghan: Sui-Tang China and Its Neighbors |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KtcvAQAAIAAJ&q=xianbei+surnames&dq=xianbei+surnames |year=1997 |publisher=Center for East Asian Studies, Western Washington University |isbn=978-0-914584-20-9 |page=35}}</ref><ref name="Ebrey2010">{{cite book |author=Patricia Buckley Ebrey |title=The Cambridge Illustrated History of China |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vr81YoYK0c4C&pg=PA93#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=25 January 2010 |publisher=Cambridge University Press |isbn=978-0-521-12433-1 |pages=93–}}</ref> [[Gao Huan]] and [[Feng Ba]] were Han rulers who adopted Xianbei culture. Feng Ba adopted a Xianbei name, Qizhifa 乞直伐.

All ethnicities who were of the literati were possibly called Haner because ethnic Xianbei were referred to as "damned Chinese" by the Northern Qi.<ref name="Eisenberg2008">{{cite book |author=Andrew Eisenberg |title=Kingship in Early Medieval China |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xjiwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA94#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=23 January 2008 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-474-3230-2 |pages=94–}}</ref> Appearing as culturally Xianbei and at the same time declaring Han Chinese ancestry was done by Gao Huan and the Han family.<ref name="Eisenberg2008 2">{{cite book |author=Andrew Eisenberg |title=Kingship in Early Medieval China |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xjiwCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA95#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=23 January 2008 |publisher=BRILL |isbn=978-90-474-3230-2 |pages=95–}}</ref> There was Xianbeification of Han.<ref>{{cite book |title=Journal of Asian History |url=https://books.google.com/?id=OIltAAAAMAAJ&q=xianbei+ized+cultural+social+sense&dq=xianbei+ized+cultural+social+sense |year=1996 |publisher=O. Harrassowitz. |page=53}}</ref>

Xianbeification happened to some sections of the Liu and Sima Han Chinese families.<ref>{{cite book|title=Journal of Asian History|url=https://books.google.com/?id=roZtAAAAMAAJ&q=The+term+was+never+used+for+Chinese+clans+like+the+Ssu-ma+and+Liu,+branches+of+which+did+in+fact+become+%22barbarized%22+through+repeated+intermarrige+with+the+Hsien-pi+elite.&dq=The+term+was+never+used+for+Chinese+clans+like+the+Ssu-ma+and+Liu,+branches+of+which+did+in+fact+become+%22barbarized%22+through+repeated+intermarrige+with+the+Hsien-pi+elite.|year=1982|publisher=O. Harrassowitz.|page=11}}</ref>

The language of the Xianbei was taught to a Han by his father who was an official.<ref name="Kuwayama1991">{{cite book |author=George Kuwayama |title=Ancient Mortuary Traditions of China: Papers on Chinese Ceramic Funerary Sculptures |url=https://books.google.com/?id=KIHYAAAAMAAJ&q=As+he+reports,+another+high+official+told+him,+%22I+have+a+boy,+already+seventeen,+who+has+a+talent+for+literary+studies.+I+am+teaching+him+the+Xianbei+language+and+how+to+strum+the+bent-neck+lute+(piba),+for+1+want+him+to+know+these+in+order+to&dq=As+he+reports,+another+high+official+told+him,+%22I+have+a+boy,+already+seventeen,+who+has+a+talent+for+literary+studies.+I+am+teaching+him+the+Xianbei+language+and+how+to+strum+the+bent-neck+lute+(piba),+for+1+want+him+to+know+these+in+order+to |date=1 January 1991 |publisher=Far Eastern Art Council, Los Angeles County Museum of Art |isbn=978-0-87587-157-8 |page=55}}</ref><ref name="Dien2007">{{cite book |author=Albert E. Dien |title=Six Dynasties Civilization |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0zp6iMZoqt0C&pg=PA286&dq=boy+seventeen+talent+xianbei+language#v=onepage&q=boy%20seventeen%20talent%20xianbei%20language&f=false |year=2007 |publisher=Yale University Press |isbn=978-0-300-07404-8 |pages=286–}}</ref><ref name="Hong2006">{{cite book |author=Wontack Hong |title=Korea and Japan in East Asian history: a tripolar approach to East Asian history |url=https://books.google.com/?id=MnEwAQAAIAAJ&q=Schreiber+(1949-5:+388)+contends+that:+%22To+provide+one%27s+own+son+with+an+elementary+knowledge+of+the+Xianbei+language,+as+a+means+of+giving+him+a+better+opportunity+for+a+political+career,+makes+sense+only+when+the+ruling&dq=Schreiber+(1949-5:+388)+contends+that:+%22To+provide+one%27s+own+son+with+an+elementary+knowledge+of+the+Xianbei+language,+as+a+means+of+giving+him+a+better+opportunity+for+a+political+career,+makes+sense+only+when+the+ruling |date=1 January 2006 |publisher=Kudara International |isbn=978-89-85567-03-9 |page=255}}</ref>

Tujue culture and language was practiced and spoken by Tang Prince [[Li Chengqian]].<ref>
