'''Gilgamesh'''{{efn|{{IPAc-en|ɡ|ɪ|l|ˈ|ɡ|ɑː|m|ɛ|ʃ}},<ref>{{cite book |first=Andrew R. |last=George |title= The Babylonian Gilgamesh Epic&nbsp;– Introduction, Critical Edition and Cuneiform Texts |location= Oxford |publisher= Oxford University Press |volume= vol. 1 and 2 |isbn= 978-0198149224 |oclc=819941336 |language= English and Akkadisch |origyear= 2003 |date=2010 |edition= reprint |page=163}}.</ref> commonly but incorrectly {{IPAc-en|ˈ|ɡ|ɪ|l|ɡ|ə|ˌ|m|ɛ|ʃ}};<ref>[http://www.dictionary.com/browse/gilgamesh "Gilgamesh"]. ''[[Random House Webster's Unabridged Dictionary]]''.</ref> {{cuneiform|𒄑𒂆𒈦}}, ''Gilgameš'', originally ''Bilgamesh'' {{cuneiform|𒄑𒉈𒂵𒈩}}. His name translates roughly to mean "The Ancestor is a Young-man",<ref>{{cite book | author-first=J.L. | url=http://enenuru.net/pdfs/Hayes_Sumerian_Grammar_2000.pdf|author-last=Hayes | title=A Manual of Sumerian Grammar and Texts}}</ref> from ''Bil.ga'' "Ancestor", Elder<ref name="Sum.Lexicon"/>{{rp|33}} and ''Mes/Mesh3'' "Young-Man".<ref name="Sum.Lexicon">{{cite book |first= J. |last=Halloran |title= Sum.Lexicon }}</ref>{{rp|174}} See also [http://psd.museum.upenn.edu/epsd1/nepsd-frame.html The Electronic Pennsylvania Sumerian Dictionary].}} was a historical king of the [[Sumer]]ian city-state of [[Uruk]], a major hero in [[ancient Mesopotamian religion|ancient Mesopotamian mythology]], and the protagonist of the ''[[Epic of Gilgamesh]]'', an epic poem written in [[Akkadian language|Akkadian]] during the late second millennium BC. He probably ruled sometime between 2800 and 2500 BC and was posthumously [[Apotheosis|deified]]. He became a major figure in Sumerian legends during the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]] ({{circa}} 2112 – {{circa}} 2004 BC). Tales of Gilgamesh's legendary exploits are narrated in five surviving Sumerian poems. The earliest of these is probably ''[[Gilgamesh, Enkidu, and the Netherworld]]'', in which Gilgamesh comes to the aid of the goddess [[Inanna]] and drives away the creatures infesting her ''huluppu'' tree. She gives him two unknown objects called a ''mikku'' and a ''pikku'', which he loses. After [[Enkidu]]'s death, his [[Shade (mythology)|shade]] tells Gilgamesh about the bleak conditions in the [[Ancient Mesopotamian Underworld|Underworld]]. The poem ''Gilgamesh and Agga'' describes Gilgamesh's revolt against his overlord [[Aga of Kish|King Agga]]. Other Sumerian poems relate Gilgamesh's defeat of the ogre [[Humbaba|Huwawa]] and the [[Bull of Heaven]] and a fifth, poorly preserved one apparently describes his death and funeral.

In later Babylonian times, these stories began to be woven into a connected narrative. The standard Akkadian ''Epic of Gilgamesh'' was composed by a scribe named [[Sîn-lēqi-unninni]], probably during the [[Kassites|Middle Babylonian Period]] ({{circa}} 1600 – {{circa}} 1155 BC), based on much older source material. In the epic, Gilgamesh is a [[demigod]] of superhuman strength who befriends the wildman [[Enkidu]]. Together, they go on adventures, defeating Humbaba (the [[East Semitic]] name for Huwawa) and the Bull of Heaven, who, in the epic, is sent to attack them by [[Ishtar]] (the East Semitic equivalent of Inanna) after Gilgamesh rejects her offer for him to become her consort. After Enkidu dies of a disease sent as punishment from the gods, Gilgamesh becomes afraid of his own death, and visits the sage [[Utnapishtim]], the survivor of the [[Gilgamesh flood myth|Great Flood]], hoping to find [[immortality]]. Gilgamesh repeatedly fails the trials set before him and returns home to Uruk, realizing that immortality is beyond his reach.

Most classical historians agree that the ''Epic of Gilgamesh'' exerted substantial influence on both the ''[[Iliad]]'' and the ''[[Odyssey]]'', two epic poems written in [[ancient Greek]] during the eighth century BC. The story of Gilgamesh's birth is described in a second-century AD anecdote from ''On the Nature of Animals'' by the Greek writer [[Claudius Aelianus|Aelian]]. Aelian relates that Gilgamesh's grandfather kept his mother under guard to prevent her from becoming pregnant, because he had been told by an [[oracle]] that his grandson would overthrow him. She became pregnant and the guards threw the child off a tower, but an eagle rescued him mid-fall and delivered him safely to an orchard, where he was raised by the gardener. The ''Epic of Gilgamesh'' was rediscovered in the [[Library of Ashurbanipal]] in 1849. After being translated in the early 1870s, it caused widespread controversy due to similarities between portions of it and the [[Hebrew Bible]]. Gilgamesh remained mostly obscure until the mid-twentieth century, but, since the late twentieth-century, he has become an increasingly prominent figure in modern culture.

==Historical king==
Most historians generally agree that Gilgamesh was a historical king of the Sumerian city-state of [[Uruk]],{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Dalley|1989|page=40}}{{sfn|Kramer|1963|pages=45–46}}{{sfn|Powell|2012|page=338}} who probably ruled sometime during the early part of the [[Early Dynastic Period (Mesopotamia)|Early Dynastic Period]] ({{circa}} 2900 – 2350 BC).{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Dalley|1989|page=40}} [[Stephanie Dalley]], a scholar of the ancient Near East, states that "precise dates cannot be given for the lifetime of Gilgamesh, but they are generally agreed to lie between 2800 and 2500 BC."{{sfn|Dalley|1989|page=40}} No contemporary mention of Gilgamesh has yet been discovered,{{sfn|Kramer|1963|pages=45–46}} but the 1955 discovery of the [[Tummal Inscription]], a thirty-four-line [[Historiography|historiographic]] text written during the reign of [[Ishbi-Erra]] ({{circa}} 1953 – {{circa}} 1920 BC), has cast considerable light on his reign.{{sfn|Kramer|1963|pages=45–46}} The inscription credits Gilgamesh with building the walls of Uruk.{{sfn|Mark|2018}} Lines eleven through fifteen of the inscription read:{{sfn|Kramer|1963|page=46}}
<blockquote><poem>
For a second time, the Tummal fell into ruin,
Gilgamesh built the Numunburra of the House of [[Enlil]].
Ur-lugal, the son of Gilgamesh,
Made the Tummal pre-eminent,
Brought [[Ninlil]] to the Tummal.{{sfn|Kramer|1963|page=46}}
</poem></blockquote>
Gilgamesh is also referred to as a king by King [[Enmebaragesi]] of Kish, a known historical figure who may have lived near Gilgamesh's lifetime.{{sfn|Mark|2018}} Furthermore, Gilgamesh is listed as one of the kings of Uruk by the [[Sumerian King List]].{{sfn|Mark|2018}} Fragments of an epic text found in Me-Turan (modern [[Tell Haddad]]) relate that at the end of his life Gilgamesh was buried under the river bed.{{sfn|Mark|2018}} The people of Uruk diverted the flow of the [[Euphrates]] passing Uruk for the purpose of burying the dead king within the river bed.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/science/nature/2982891.stm | title=Gilgamesh tomb believed found | publisher=BBC News | date=29 April 2003 | accessdate=12 October 2017}}</ref>{{sfn|Mark|2018}}

==Deification and legendary exploits==
===Sumerian poems===
[[File:Le dieu de l ete et dumuzi.jpg|thumb|upright=1.5|Akkadian cylinder seal impression from [[Girsu]] ({{circa}} 2340 - 2150 BC) showing a mythological scene.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=32–33}} The figure in the center appears to be a god, perhaps Gilgamesh, who is bending the trunk of a tree into a curve as he chops it down.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=32–33}} Underneath the tree, a god ascending from the Underworld hands a mace-like object to a goddess.{{sfn|Kramer|1961|pages=32–33}}]]

It is certain that, during the later Early Dynastic Period, Gilgamesh was worshipped as a god at various locations across Sumer.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}} In the twenty-first century BC, [[Utu-hengal]], the king of Uruk, adopted Gilgamesh as his patron deity.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}} The kings of the [[Third Dynasty of Ur]] ({{circa}} 2112 – {{circa}} 2004 BC) were especially fond of Gilgamesh,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}} calling him their "divine brother" and "friend".{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}} King [[Shulgi]] of Ur (2029 – 1982 BC) declared himself the son of [[Lugalbanda]] and [[Ninsun]] and the brother of Gilgamesh.{{sfn|Mark|2018}} Over the centuries, there may have been a gradual accretion of stories about Gilgamesh, some possibly derived from the real lives of other historical figures, such as [[Gudea]], the Second Dynasty ruler of [[Lagash]] (2144–2124 BC).<ref>{{cite book | author-link=N.K. Sandars | first=N.K. | last=Sandars |chapter=Introduction|title=The Epic of Gilgamesh| publisher=Penguin | date=1972}}</ref> Prayers inscribed in clay tablets address Gilgamesh as a judge of the dead in the Underworld.{{sfn|Mark|2018}}

During this period, a large number of myths and legends developed surrounding Gilgamesh.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Kramer|1963|page=45}}<ref name="Norton Anthology"/>{{rp|95}}{{sfn|George|2003|page=141}} Five independent Sumerian poems narrating various exploits of Gilgamesh have survived to the present.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}} Gilgamesh's first appearance in literature is probably in the Sumerian poem ''[[Gilgamesh, Enkidu, and the Netherworld]]''.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=30}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}<ref>[[Electronic Text Corpus of Sumerian Literature|ETCSL]] [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr1814.htm 1.8.1.4]</ref> The narrative begins with a ''huluppu'' tree—perhaps, according to the Sumerologist [[Samuel Noah Kramer]], a willow,{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=33}} growing on the banks of the river [[Euphrates]].{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=33}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=172}} The goddess Inanna moves the tree to her garden in [[Uruk]] with the intention to carve it into a throne once it is fully grown.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=33}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=172}} The tree grows and matures, but the serpent "who knows no charm," the ''[[Anzû (mythology)|Anzû]]''-bird, and ''Lilitu'', the Sumerian forerunner to the [[Lilith]] of Jewish folklore, all take up residence within the tree, causing Inanna to cry with sorrow.{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=33}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=172}} Gilgamesh, who in this story is portrayed as Inanna's brother, comes along and slays the serpent, causing the ''Anzû''-bird and Lilitu to flee.{{snf|Kramer|1961|pages=33–34}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=172}} Gilgamesh's companions chop down the tree and carve its wood into a bed and a throne, which they give to Inanna.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=140}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=172}} Inanna responds by fashioning a ''pikku'' and a ''mikku'' (probably a drum and drumsticks respectively, although the exact identifications are uncertain),{{snf|Kramer|1961|page=34}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}} which she gives to Gilgamesh as a reward for his heroism.{{snf|Wolkstein|Kramer|1983|page=9}}{{sfn|Mark|2018}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=172}} Gilgamesh loses the ''pikku'' and ''mikku'' and asks who will retrieve them.{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|pages=172–173}} Enkidu descends to the Underworld to find them,{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=173}} but disobeys the strict laws of the Underworld and is therefore required to remain there forever.{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=173}} The remaining portion of the poem is a dialogue in which Gilgamesh asks the [[Shade (mythology)|shade]] of Enkidu questions about the Underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|pages=172–173}}

''Gilgamesh and Agga'' describes Gilgamesh's successful revolt against his overlord [[Aga of Kish|Agga]], the king of the city-state of [[Kish (Sumer)|Kish]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}<ref>ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr1811.htm 1.8.1.1]</ref> ''Gilgamesh and Huwawa'' describes how Gilgamesh and his servant [[Enkidu]], aided by the help of fifty volunteers from Uruk, defeat the monster [[Huwawa]], an ogre appointed by the god [[Enlil]], the ruler of the gods, as the guardian of the [[Cedar Forest]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=167}}<ref>ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr1815.htm 1.8.1.5]</ref> Huwawa has the "teeth of a dragon, the face of a lion, a roar like the stormflood, a mouth like fire; his breath [is] death; no one [can] escape him."{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=167}} Gilgamesh and his fifty-one companions hew through seven cedar trees to reach Huwawa's chamber, where they corner him.{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=168}} Gilgamesh strikes Huwawa, loosening his teeth;{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=168}} Huwawa attempts to appeal for mercy to Gilgamesh and the sun-god [[Utu]],{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=168}} but the heroes behead him anyway.{{sfn|Fontenrose|1980|page=168}} In the end, the gods condemn Enkidu to death due to his lack of compassion for Huwawa.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=90}}

In ''Gilgamesh and the Bull of Heaven'', Gilgamesh and Enkidu slay the [[Bull of Heaven]], who has been sent to attack them by the goddess [[Inanna]].{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=24}}<ref>ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr1812.htm 1.8.1.2]</ref> The plot of this poem differs substantially from the corresponding scene in the later Akkadian ''Epic of Gilgamesh''.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=24–25}} In the Sumerian poem, Inanna does not seem to ask Gilgamesh to become her consort as she does in the later Akkadian epic.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|page=24}} Furthermore, while she is coercing her father [[Anu|An]] to give her the Bull of Heaven, rather than threatening to raise the dead to eat the living as she does in the later epic, she merely threatens to let out a "cry" that will reach the earth.{{sfn|Tigay|2002|pages=24–25}} A poem known as the ''Death of Gilgamesh'' is very poorly preserved,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}<ref>ETCSL [http://etcsl.orinst.ox.ac.uk/section1/tr1813.htm 1.8.1.3]</ref> but appears to describe a major state funeral followed by the arrival of the deceased in the Underworld.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}} It is possible that the modern scholars who gave the poem its title may have misinterpreted it,{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}} and the poem may actually be about the death of Enkidu.{{sfn|Black|Green|1992|page=89}}

