{{italic title}}
The '''''Polish–Hungarian Chronicle'''''{{sfn|Macartney|1953|p=173}}{{sfn|Györffy|1994|p=142}} or '''''Hungarian–Polish Chronicle'''''{{sfn|Steinhübel|2011|p=19}} (from {{lang-la|Chronicon Hungarico-Polonicum}}) is a medieval [[chronicle]] which exists in two redactions in five [[manuscript]]s kept in Polish libraries.{{sfn|Grzesik|2003|p=98}}<!--One is the Zamojski Codex from the second half of the 14th century and its copy from the 15th century.{{sfn|Macartney|1953|p=173}}--> Its full title is '''''Chronicle of the Hungarians Attached to and Mixed with Chronicles of the Poles, and the Life of Saint Stephen''''' (''Cronica Ungarorum juncta et mixta cum cronicis Polonorum, et vita sancti Stephani'').{{sfn|Macartney|1953|p=173}} According to the Hungarian historian [[György Györffy]], it "contains a fair number of absurdities".{{sfn|Györffy|1994|p=142}}

The original chronicle was probably composed in the 1220s or 1230s at the court of Duke [[Coloman of Galicia-Lodomeria|Coloman of Slavonia]], the deposed [[Kingdom of Galicia–Volhynia|King of Galicia and Lodomeria]]. The original manuscript was taken to Poland by Coloman's widow, Salomea, after 1241. It tells the story of the Hungarians from the reign of "Aquila" ([[Attila the Hun]]) to that of [[Ladislaus I of Hungary|Ladislaus I]].{{sfn|Grzesik|2012}}

